{{Infobox scientist | name = Alfred J. Eggers, Jr. | image = Alfred J. Eggers - GPN-2000-001586.jpg | caption = Al Eggers at NACA Ames facility in 1956 | birth_date = {{birth date|1922|6|24|mf=y}}| birth_place = [[Omaha]], [[Nebraska]], [[United States|U.S.]] | death_date = {{death date and age|2006|9|22|1922|6|24|mf=y}} | death_place = [[Atherton, California|Atherton]], [[California]], [[United States|U.S.]] | nationality = [[United States|American]] | field = [[Aerospace Engineer]] | work_institution = [[NACA]], [[NASA]] | alma_mater = [[University of Omaha]], [[Stanford University]] | known_for = [[supersonic flight]], [[atmospheric reentry|re-entry physics]] }}
'''Alfred J. Eggers, Jr.''' (June 24, 1922 &ndash; September 22, 2006) was [[NASA]]'s Assistant Administrator for Policy and devoted efforts to determine the influence of aviation technology in world peace and lectured widely.
Eggers specialized in hypersonic and spaceflight research including the development of new [[wind tunnel]] and ballistic range facilities. He went to work for the [[National Advisory Committee for Aeronautics|NACA]] at [[Ames Research Center|Ames Aeronautical Laboratory]] in 1944 after completing the [[V-12 Navy College Training Program]].<ref name="v-12-program">{{cite web |url=http://grin.hq.nasa.gov/ABSTRACTS/GPN-2000-001586.html |title=GRIN Great Images in NASA - Alfred J. Eggers |accessdate=September 24, 2011 |author= |publisher=NASA History Office, 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926220355/http://grin.hq.nasa.gov/ABSTRACTS/GPN-2000-001586.html |archivedate=September 26, 2011 |df= }}</ref>
==Biography==
In 1954, he became Division Chief of the Vehicle Environment Division, which was composed of a physics branch, an entry simulation branch, a structural dynamics branch, the 3.5 foot [[hypersonic wind tunnel]] branch and the hypervelocity ballistic range branch. In 1958, Eggers headed up the Manned Satellite Team, which was to design a practical system for a satellite while recommending a suitable research program. This ultimately lead to Ames developing and managing the [[Pioneer program]] of planetary exploration probes. Although Eggers is most famous for his pioneering work on atmospheric reentry with a blunt body, arguably his greatest achievement was his work on supersonic interference lift. This work lead directly to the [[XB-70 Valkyrie]] supersonic bomber.{{citation needed|date=November 2010}}
In May 1964, Eggers was appointed Deputy Associate Administrator for Advanced Research and Technology. He became Assistant Administrator for Policy in January 1968, and served until March 1971.<ref name="v-12-program"/> From 1969 to 1970, Eggers was a visiting professor at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mit.edu/~cousot/MintaMartinLecture/index.html|title=P. Cousot, Minta Martin Lecture, Friday May 13, 2005|date=May 1, 2005|accessdate=March 21, 2010|publisher=[[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]]}}</ref>
Following his career at NASA, Eggers took a position as Assistant Director for Research Applications at the [[National Science Foundation]].<ref name="v-12-program"/>
His assistant, [[Clarence A. Syvertson|C. A. "Sy" Syvertson]] became Director of NASA Ames Research Center during probably its most productive years.{{citation needed|date=November 2010}} A close friend of both was the legendary aerodynamicist, R. T. Jones.{{citation needed|date=November 2010}}
