{{BLP primary sources|date=June 2010}} {{Infobox writer <!--For more information, see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]].--> | name = D. A. Clarke | honorific_prefix = | honorific_suffix = | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | pseudonym = De Clarke or DeAnander | birth_name = | birth_date = <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | birth_place = | death_date = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | death_place = | resting_place = | occupation = | language = English | nationality = [[United States|American]] | ethnicity = | citizenship = | education = | alma_mater = | period = | genre = <!-- or: | genres = --> | subject = <!-- or: | subjects = --> | movement = [[Radical feminism]] | notablework = ''Justice Is A Woman With A Sword'' | spouse = <!-- or: | spouses = --> | partner = <!-- or: | partners = --> | children = | relatives = | awards = | signature = | signature_alt = | years_active = 1980–present | module = | website = | portaldisp = yes }} '''D. A. Clarke''' (also known as '''De Clarke''' and '''DeAnander''') is a [[radical feminism|radical feminist]] essayist and activist in the [[United States of America]] who has been active since 1980.
== Career == Much of Clarke's writing addresses the link between violence against women and [[market economics]], although she may be best known for her 1991 essay "''Justice Is A Woman With A Sword''".<ref>{{Cite news | last = Clarke | first = D.A. | title = Justice is a woman with a sword | url = http://www.nostatusquo.com/ACLU/Porn/Justice.html | work = [[Nikki Craft#1990s and onward|NoStatusQuo]] | publisher = [[Nikki Craft]] | date = 1991 }}</ref> In that essay, which she has updated twice for editions of the anthology ''Transforming a Rape Culture'', she argues that [[feminist theory]] has taken a [[dogma]]tic approach to [[nonviolence]] and that women's [[self-defense]], violent feminist [[activism]], and the encouragement of positive media portrayals of violent women (such as in ''[[Kill Bill]]'' or ''[[Xena: Warrior Princess]]'') have not been given the serious consideration they should receive and that their dismissal from mainstream feminism, while it may ultimately be desirable, has not been based on a properly thorough analysis. Her most popular work, however, may be the one least often correctly attributed to her: the early poem ''privilege'', which has been found on dorm refrigerators and bulletin boards ascribed to 'Anonymous.'<ref>{{citation | last = Clarke | first = D.A. | contribution = privilege | editor-last = Clarke | editor-first = D.A. | title = Banshee | publisher = Peregrine Press | location = Portland, Maine | year = 1981 | contribution-url = http://www.nostatusquo.com/~de/banshee/privilege.html | ref = harv | postscript = .}}</ref> In this case, at least, Anonymous really was a woman.
In addition to being published in print anthologies, much of her work has appeared online. Clarke also had brief visibility as an amateur/indie musician, with one album "messages" released on cassette in the mid 80's.
