{{Infobox military person |name = Henry III of Nassau-Dillenburg-Dietz |birth_date = 12 January 1483 |death_date = 14 September 1538 |image = 'Portrait of Hendrik III, Count of Nassau-Breda', oil on panel painting by Jan Gossart (Mabuse).jpg |caption = Henry III by [[Jan Gossaert]] |rank = [[Captain General]] |birth_place = [[Siegen]], [[Nassau (state)|County of Nassau]] |death_place = [[Breda]], [[Duchy of Brabant]] |allegiance = [[Habsburg|Habsburg dynasty]] |battles = [[War of the League of Cambrai]] [[Italian War of 1521]] }} [[Count]] '''Henry III of Nassau-Dillenburg-Dietz''' (12 January 1483, [[Siegen]] – 14 September 1538, [[Breda]]), [[Lord]] (from 1530 [[Baron]]) of [[Breda]], Lord of the [[Lek (manor)|Lek]], of [[Diez, Germany|Dietz]], etc. was a count of the [[House of Nassau]].
He was the son of Count [[John V of Nassau-Dillenburg]] and [[Elisabeth of Hesse-Marburg]].{{sfn|Guenther|1995|p=5}} His younger brother was [[William I, Count of Nassau-Dillenburg]] (the father of [[William the Silent]]).
==Career== In 1499 Henry's uncle, count [[Engelbert II of Nassau-Breda|Engelbert II]], invited Henry to the [[Seventeen Provinces|Burgundian Netherlands]] as his heir.{{sfn|Guenther|1995|p=5}} He travelled with [[Philip the Handsome]] to [[Castile (historical region)|Castile]] in 1501-1503. Upon the death of his uncle in 1504 Henry inherited the Nassau possessions in the Netherlands, including the wealthy lordship of [[Breda]] in the [[duchy of Brabant]]. The next year he was chosen a [[knight of the Golden Fleece]]. He again travelled to [[Spain]] in 1505-1506. He became a close confidant of the young [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles V]] as well as his [[Chamberlain (office)|Chamberlain]] (1510), becoming his Upper Chamberlain upon the death of [[William de Croÿ|William of Croÿ-Chièvres]] in 1521. The good relations between Charles and Henry is evident in the fact that Charles did not name a new Upper Chamberlain after Henry's death. Henry was named [[Grand Huntsman of Brabant]], a position at court he held until the end of his life.
In 1519 he was part of the delegation that had Charles chosen [[king of the Romans]]. He was also prominently present at Charles' coronation to [[Holy Roman Emperor|Emperor]] in [[Bologna]] in 1530. He was a member of the [[Privy Council]] of Charles since 1515 and of the Privy Council of Archduchess [[Margaret of Austria (1480-1530)|Margaret of Austria]] between 1525-1526. He temporarily served as [[Stadtholder]] of the conquered parts of [[Guelders]] and was Stadtholder of [[Holland]] and [[Zeeland]] between 1515 and 1521. Henry was again in Spain between 1522 and 1530 (accompanying Charles) and in 1533-1534 (with his wife and son).
==Military commander== Henry served as an important military commander in the Netherlands, defending [[Duchy of Brabant|Brabant]] from [[Guelders]] in 1508. He was [[Captain General]] in the war with Guelders between 1511 and 1513, and fought with [[Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor|Maximilian of Austria]] against [[France]] until 1514, participating in the [[Battle of Guinegate (1513)|battle of Guinegate]] (1513). He again commanded the armies against Guelders and [[France]] between 1516 and 1521, defeating the [[Black Band (landsknechts)|Black Band]], which was in the employ of [[Charles of Guelders]], in 1518 and defeating [[Robert van der Marck]], Lord of [[Sedan, France|Sedan]] in 1521. He also repelled [[Francis I of France]], who invaded [[County of Hainaut|Hainaut]] that same year. Subsequently Henry conquered [[Tournai]]. [[File:Castle Breda.gif|thumb|180px|right|The Castle of Breda after it was rebuilt in the Renaissance style.]] [[File:Guilliam van Schoor and Gillis van Tilborgh 001.jpg|thumb|300px|left|[[Guilliam van Schoor]] (landscape) and [[Gillis van Tilborch]] (figures). ''The Palace of Nassau in Brussels''. 1658, [[Royal Museums of Fine Arts of Belgium]]]]
==Beliefs== Although Henry, who attended the [[Diet of Augsburg]] in 1530, was at first not averse to [[Martin Luther]] and his [[Lutheranism|teachings]], he later followed Charles' example and remained a staunch [[Roman Catholicism|Catholic]]. He didn't approve of the choice of his brother William, who did become a Lutheran, but remained supportive of him throughout his life. He was very impressed with the [[Renaissance]] and especially its arts, examples of which he encountered on his journeys to [[Spain]] and [[Italy]]. For example, he commissioned Italian [[architect]] [[Tommaso Vincidor|Tomasso Vincidor da Bologna]] to completely rebuild his [[castle]] at Breda in a renaissance style in 1536, one of the first of such buildings north of the [[Alps]]. However, his interests seem to have been superficial. [[Desiderius Erasmus]] only considered him a "[[Platonic love|platonic]] friend of science".
==Family life and death== [[File:PraalgrafengelbrechtIIbreda.jpg|240px|thumb|The grave monument of Engelbert II at the {{lang|nl|[[Grote kerk (Breda)|Grote kerk]]}} in [[Breda]], [[Netherlands]]. Both Henry III and his son René are buried here.]] Henry married three times: *On 3 August 1503 Henry III married firstly [[Louise-Françoise of Savoy]] (° bef. 1486 - † 17 September 1511).{{sfn|Guenther|1995|p=5}} They had no children. *In May 1515 Henry III married secondly [[Claudia of Châlon]] (° 1498 – † 31 May 1521).{{sfn|Guenther|1995|p=5}} They had one son, [[René of Châlon]] (° 5 February 1519 - † 18 July 1544), who became [[prince of Orange]] in 1530 on the death of Claudia's brother [[Philibert of Châlon|Philibert]]. *On 26 June 1524 Henry III married thirdly [[Mencía de Mendoza|Mencia de Mendoza y Fonseca]] (° 30 November 1508 – † 4 January 1554).{{sfn|Guenther|1995|p=5}} They had one son, born in March 1527, who lived only a few hours.
Henry had no further legitimate children, although he is known to have had some illegitimate offspring, amongst them [[Nassau-Corroy|Alexis of Nassau-Corroy]] and Isabelle of Nassau, both legitimised after the death of their father, and both had an impressive descendance. One of his descendants is [[Philippe François de Berghes, 1st Prince of Grimberghen]].
His third marriage to Mencia de Mendoza y Fonseca was mainly encouraged by Charles V, as part of his plan to make the nobility of [[Spain]] and the [[Seventeen Provinces|Low Countries]] mix. Henry was however never really liked by the Spaniards, who regarded him as a loud and barbarian [[German people|German]] [[parvenu]]. Upon his death in 1538 he was succeeded by his only son, but René was himself slain in battle only a few years later in 1544. Henry lies buried beneath the grave monument he had erected for his uncle Engelbert in the {{lang|nl|[[Grote kerk (Breda)|Grote kerk]]}} at Breda. [[File:Blason Nassau-Vianden.svg|thumb|right|Coat of arms of Henry III. The 1st and 4th quarters show the arms of Nassau. The 2nd and 3rd show the arms of the lordship of Breda & Vianden.<ref>{{cite book |title=Armorial general|first=Johannes Baptist|last =Rietstap|publisher=Genealogical Publishing Co.|year=2003|volume= vol.2|page=297|isbn=0-8063-4811-9}}</ref>]]
