{{Infobox person | name = Mary Jackson | image = | caption = | birth_date = {{birth date|1910|11|22}} | birth_place = [[Milford, Michigan]], U.S. | death_date = {{death date and age|2005|12|10|1910|11|22|mf=yes}} | death_place = [[Los Angeles, California]], U.S. | occupation = Actress }}
'''Mary Jackson''' (November 22, 1910 - December 10, 2005) was an American [[character actress]] whose nearly fifty-year career began in 1950 and was spent almost entirely on television. She is best known for the role of the lovelorn [[List of The Waltons characters#Emily Baldwin|Emily Baldwin]] in ''[[The Waltons]]'' and was the original choice to play [[Alice Horton]] in the daytime soap opera ''[[Days of Our Lives]]''. She in fact played the part in the unaired [[television pilot|pilot]] although the role was subsequently taken by [[Frances Reid]].<ref>[http://www.mg.co.za/article/2005-12-20-waltons-actress-dies-at-95 "Waltons Actress Dies at 95"], mg.co.za, 20 December 2005.</ref>
==Early years== Born in the village of [[Milford, Michigan]],<ref>Rossiter, Joe. [https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/freep/access/1778468561.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Dec+14%2C+2005&author=JOE+ROSSITER&pub=Detroit+Free+Press&desc=MARY+JACKSON%3A+'WALTONS'+ACTRESS+KEPT+MILFORD+CLOSE&pqatl=google "Mary Jackson: 'Waltons' Actress Kept Milford Close"], ''Detroit Free Press'', December 14, 2005, page B5.</ref><ref>Donaldson, Stan. [https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/freep/access/1755491361.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Oct+02%2C+2006&author=STAN+DONALDSON&pub=Detroit+Free+Press&desc=ACTRESS+WILLS+PAIR+OF+OLD+HOMES+TO+HER+HOMETOWN&pqatl=google "Actress Wills Pair of Old Homes to Her Hometown"], ''Detroit Free Press'', October 2, 2006, page B1.</ref> She earned a bachelor's degree from [[Western Michigan University]] in 1932.<ref>[http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=DTNB&s_site=detnews&f_site=detnews&f_sitename=Detroit+News%2C+The+%28MI%29&p_multi=DTNB&p_theme=gannett&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=10E812E61CDACF70&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM "Mary Jackson, Milford: Actress played Miss Emily in 'The Waltons' TV series"], ''The Detroit News'', December 14, 2005.</ref>
She was a schoolteacher during the [[Great Depression]] for one year before pursuing her interest in the theater.<ref>[https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/941675671.html?dids=941675671:941675671&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Dec+15%2C+2005&author=&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=Obituaries%3B+PASSINGS%3B+Mary+Jackson%2C+95%3B+Actress+Known+for+Her+Role+on+'The+Waltons'&pqatl=google "Mary Jackson, 95, Actress Known for Her Role on 'The Waltons'"], ''Los Angeles Times'', December 15, 2005, p. B11</ref>
She returned to college, enrolling in [[Michigan State University]]'s fine arts program and, subsequently, began her performing career on Chicago stage, in summer stock and, at the start of the period referenced as the [[Golden Age of Television]], in [[New York City]] and, as the 1960s began, in [[Hollywood]].<ref>[https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/945033371.html?dids=945033371:945033371&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Dec+22%2C+2005&author=&pub=The+Washington+Post&desc=Mary+Jackson+Character+Actr+...&pqatl=google "Mary Jackson Character Actress"], ''The Washington Post'', December 22, 2005, page B08.</ref>
Mary Jackson was survived by her husband of 68 years, Griffin Bancroft Jr., to whom she was married from July 4, 1937 until her death, in [[Los Angeles]], from [[Parkinson's disease]], two-and-a-half weeks just after her 95th birthday.<ref>[http://www.contactmusic.com/news-article/waltons-star-dies-aged-95 "Waltons Star Dies Aged 95"], ContactMusic.com, December 16, 2005.</ref>
Always close to her Michigan roots, Jackson was a charter member of the Milford Historical Society. Jackson was instrumental in 1988 in raising money to [http://www.milfordhistory.org/jackson_obit.html rebuild the Oak Grove Cemetery Bridge] over the Huron River - a bridge that connected the Village of Milford to its oldest burial grounds. Jackson was buried at Oak Grove Cemetery, in her hometown of Milford, Michigan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/12676623|title=Mary Jackson (1910-2005) - Find A Grave Memorial|website=www.findagrave.com}}</ref>
