{{Infobox company | type = [[Privately-held|Private]] | name = Soothe | logo = Soothe Logo.png | industry = Therapeutic | founded = {{Start date and age|2013|08}} | founder = Merlin Kauffman & Bradley Herman | key_people = Merlin Kauffman (CEO) | hq_location_city = [[Los Angeles, California]] | hq_location_country = United States | services = [[Massage]] | website = {{URL|https://www.soothe.com}} }}
'''Soothe''' is a [[Multinational corporation|multi-national]] [[massage]] service provider based out of [[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, California]]. The company allows users to request the services of a [[massage therapist]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2016/05/05/now-you-can-order-a-massage-like-uber/|title=Now you can order a massage like Uber|last=Mitchell|first=Timothy|date=2016-05-05|website=New York Post|access-date=2017-09-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/health/bs-hs-on-demand-spa-beauty-20160907-story.html|title=On-demand apps, providers bring massage, makeup, hairstyling to your door|last=Eatough|first=Allison|date=2016-09-07|work=Baltimore Sun|access-date=2017-09-11|language=en-US}}</ref> Since its launch in 2014, the mostly [[mobile app]]-based company has received significant press coverage and has expanded its service area to include many cities and counties in the United States. It also provides services in a few cities in Australia, Canada and the UK.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.digitaltrends.com/home/soothe-massage-on-demand/|title=Soothe, the 'Uber for massage,' wants to bring pampering straight to your door|last=Chang|first=Lulu|date=2017-09-13|work=Digital Trends|access-date=2017-10-12|language=en-US}}</ref>
== History == Soothe was founded in August 2013. It was created by Merlin Kauffman,<ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=http://www.indystar.com/story/life/2016/03/22/indy-natives-app-delivers-massages-door/81546302/|title=Indy native's app delivers massages to door|last=Bailey|first=Leslie|date=2016-03-22|work=Indianapolis Star|access-date=2017-09-10|language=en}}</ref> CEO & cofounder,<ref name=":7">{{Cite news|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/business/sdut-mothersday-apps-2015may08-story.html|title=Mother's Day gifts on demand|last=Van Grove|first=Jennifer|date=2015-05-08|work=The San Diego Union-Tribune|access-date=2017-09-10|language=en-US}}</ref> and Bradley Herman, former CTO & cofounder.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.crowdfundinsider.com/2014/09/50536-soothe-app-uber-massage-now-trending-angellist-massage-delivered/|title=Soothe App - Uber for Massage - Now Trending on AngelList: Massage Delivered {{!}} Crowdfund Insider|date=2014-09-23|work=Crowdfund Insider|access-date=2018-02-14|language=en-US}}</ref> Kauffman developed the idea behind the service while studying at the [[Harvard Business School]].<ref name=":9">{{Cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2015/08/12/an-investor-just-poured-10-6-million-into-an-on-demand-massage-startup/|title=Soothes raises $10.6 million for its on-demand massage service|last=Kokalitcheva|first=Kia|website=Fortune|access-date=2017-09-10}}</ref> He was a [[Domain name speculation|domain-name investor]] who started as a teenager.<ref name=":1" /><ref name=":10">{{Cite news|url=https://www.inc.com/christine-lagorio/massages-on-demand.html|title=Welcome to the Billion-Dollar, Uber-for-Massages Industry|last=Lagorio-Chafkin|first=Christine|date=2016-04-01|work=Inc.|access-date=2017-09-10|language=en}}</ref> As an adult, he invested four hundred thousand of his own money to start the business. The company first began operating in the [[Los Angeles]] area where it was based.<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonian.com/2015/06/24/need-a-massage-right-now-theres-an-app-for-that/|title=Need a Massage RIGHT NOW? There's an App for That.|last=Cunningham|first=Caroline|date=2015-06-24|website=Washingtonian|access-date=2017-09-10}}</ref> It also has a second headquarters in [[Las Vegas]], Nevada.<ref name=":10" /><ref name=":11">{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/briansolomon/2016/03/10/soothe-raises-35-million-to-accelerate-on-demand-massage-growth/|title=Soothe Raises $35 Million To Accelerate On-Demand Massage Growth|last=Solomon|first=Brian|work=Forbes|access-date=2017-09-10|language=en}}</ref>
As of December 2014, the service had 300 licensed massage therapists in Los Angeles and also covered [[Austin, Texas|Austin]], [[Miami]], [[Orange County, California|Orange County]], [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]] and [[San Diego]].<ref name=":6">{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailybreeze.com/technology/20141214/massage-app-soothe-connects-licensed-massage-therapists-with-clients|title=Massage app Soothe connects licensed massage therapists with clients|last=England-Nelson|first=Jordan|date=2014-12-15|work=Daily Breeze|access-date=2017-09-10|language=en}}</ref> In August 2015, the company received $10.6 million in funding from [[Riverside Company|The Riverside Company]]. By this point, the company had expanded to a total of 13 cities which included [[Chicago]], [[Seattle]], and [[San Francisco]].<ref name=":9" /> In its March 2016 Series B funding, the company raised an additional $35 million.<ref name=":11" /> It had expanded to twenty-two areas in the US, including [[Atlanta]] and [[Indianapolis]].<ref name=":1" /> Soothe had a total of more than 3,200 massage therapists across the nation. It also operates at a loss and planned to continue to do so “for the foreseeable future”.<ref name=":11" /> However, the company reported a monthly revenue of $1.2 million as of March 2016.<ref name=":8">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-03-10/on-demand-massage-apps-are-thriving|title=On-Demand Massage Apps Are Thriving|last=Wang|first=Selina|date=2016-03-10|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=2017-09-10}}</ref>
As of April 2016, Soothe’s coverage area also included such cities as [[Houston]], [[Minneapolis]], [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]], and [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]]. It had also expanded services to Canada by including [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]].<ref name=":5">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/05/01/travel/airbnb-spas-hotels.html|title=How to Bring the Hotel Spa to Your Airbnb|last=Rosenbloom|first=Stephanie|date=2016-04-26|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-09-10|language=en-US}}</ref> The company also began servicing in Europe with [[London]] becoming the first city across the Atlantic.<ref name=":3">{{Cite news|url=http://www.instyle.com/beauty/health-fitness/on-demand-massage-apps|title=I Might Be Addicted to On-Demand Massage Apps|last=Gould|first=Wendy Rose|date=2016-07-27|work=InStyle.com|access-date=2017-09-10|language=en}}</ref>
In July 2016, the company has signed-up corporate clients like [[Facebook]], [[Hulu]], and [[Microsoft]]. According to the company, the move was partly motivated by a desire to smooth-out demand and mitigate the spike in service requests outside of the regular nine to five corporate business hours.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/soothe-on-demand-massage-startup-launches-business-product-2016-7|title=This startup works with companies like Facebook and Microsoft to give employees on-demand massages|last=McAlone|first=Nathan|date=2016-07-21|work=Business Insider|access-date=2017-09-10|language=en}}</ref> By February 2017, the service was available in 51 cities in the US while also adding services to [[Toronto|Toronto, Canada.]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.star-telegram.com/living/indulge/article132694894.html|title=Six apps that bring pampering services straight to your hotel room|last=Bauso|first=Anne Olivia|date=2017-02-14|work=Star-Telegram|access-date=2017-09-10|language=en}}</ref> In summer 2017, the company launched two locations in Australia by expanding its services to [[Sydney]] and [[Melbourne]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mybusiness.com.au/leadership/3028-real-life-scaling-a-business-into-a-global-empire|title=Real life: Scaling a business into a global empire|last=Zuchetti|first=Adam|date=2017-06-13|work=My Business|access-date=2017-09-10|language=en}}</ref>
On May 2, 2018, Soothe raised $31 million in Series C funding from The Riverside Company.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/05/02/massage-on-demand-company-soothe-raises-31-million/|title=Massage-on-demand company, Soothe, raises $31 million – TechCrunch|website=techcrunch.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-05-02}}</ref>
